    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-06-23T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-06-23T05:00:00-05:00" n="798"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d798">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.6363/280: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-06-23T19:00:00+09:00"
                            >June 23, 1936—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 23—2:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>137. Embassy’s 78, March 23, 7 p.m.</p>
                <p>1. Yesterday the local representatives of the foreign oil interests were
                    requested by the Ministry of Commerce and Industry to submit immediately a
                    statement along the following lines. <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <list>
                            <item>“(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) The two companies will fulfill the
                                obligation of stock holding;</item>
                            <item>(<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) Accordingly, they are now in process of
                                discussing special arrangements to that end”.</item>
                        </list>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p rend="flushleft">The local representatives believe it impossible for their
                    principals to agree to part (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) of the statement.</p>
                <p>2. Today, in the course of an informal conversation, in the presence of
                        Sansom<note n="80" xml:id="d798fn80">Sir George B. Sansom, British
                        Commercial Counselor in Japan.</note> and Dickover,<note n="81"
                        xml:id="d798fn81">Erie B. Dickover, First Secretary of Embassy in
                        Japan.</note> Yoshino, Vice Minister for Commerce and Industry, stated that
                    he would accept a statement as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The companies are now negotiating a special arrangement to enable them
                            to fulfill their obligations under the petroleum law and have reached an
                            agreement in principle”.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p rend="flushleft">This is believed to be the minimum which Yoshino can accept in
                    order to give unreduced trade quotas from July 1st to the foreign oil interests
                    and to continue the postponement of the granting of additional refining
                    permits.</p>
                <pb facs="0892" n="797" xml:id="pg_797"/>
                <p>3. The local representatives are telegraphing the foregoing statement to their
                    principals and in view of the urgency are pressing for an early reply.</p>
                <p>4. Yoshino also stated that it would be impossible further to postpone
                    enforcement of the stock holding provision of the law. I therefore do not
                    believe it advisable to make the representations authorized in the Department’s
                    33, March 20, 6 p.m., except as a last resort.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
